  "text": "The LLVM IR type system flows from high-level type creation through context management to machine-level code generation in the following chain:\n\n## Type Class Hierarchy\nThe foundation is established in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/Type.h` which defines the base `Type` class. This class uses an enum `TypeID` to identify type categories. The `Type` class maintains immutability and uniqueness: only one instance of each type exists, enforced through private constructors and static factory methods.\n\nIn `llvm/include/llvm/IR/DerivedTypes.h`, the derived types extend Type:\n- `IntegerType` (line 42): Represents arbitrary-width integers. The bit width is stored in the `SubclassData` field. Created via `IntegerType::get()` (line 66)\n- `FunctionType` (line 105): Represents functions with return type and parameter list. The return type is at `ContainedTys[0]` and parameters follow\n- `StructType` (line 218): Represents struct types with elements stored in `ContainedTys`. Supports both literal (uniqued) and identified struct types\n\n## Context Ownership and Type Storage\nThe `llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContextImpl.h` file defines `LLVMContextImpl` (line 1620) which owns and manages all types in a context. Key type storage structures (lines 1746-1775):\n- Primitive types: `VoidTy`, `FloatTy`, `DoubleTy`, etc. stored directly as members\n- `IntegerTypes`: DenseMap<unsigned, IntegerType*> caching integer types by bit width\n- `FunctionTypes`: DenseSet<FunctionType*, FunctionTypeKeyInfo> for uniquing function types\n- `AnonStructTypes`: DenseSet<StructType*, AnonStructTypeKeyInfo> for literal structs\n- `NamedStructTypes`: StringMap<StructType*> for named structs\n- `TargetExtTypes`: DenseSet<TargetExtType*, TargetExtTypeKeyInfo> for target-specific types\n\nThe KeyInfo structures (lines 93-237) define equality and hashing for types, enabling structural uniquing.\n\n## IR Type to Machine Type Lowering\nThe conversion from LLVM IR types to target machine types happens through three key stages:\n\n1. **Type Analysis** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/Analysis.cpp`):\n   - `ComputeValueTypes()` (line 72) recursively decomposes aggregate IR types into scalar types\n   - `ComputeValueVTs()` (line 119) converts IR types to Extended Value Types (EVT) using TargetLowering\n\n2. **IR Type to EVT Conversion** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/ValueTypes.cpp`):\n   - `EVT::getEVT()` (line 301) is the core conversion function that maps LLVM Type objects to machine value types\n   - For IntegerType: calls `getIntegerVT()` with the bit width\n   - For VectorType: calls `getVectorVT()` recursively on element types\n   - For other types: delegates to `MVT::getVT()`\n\n3. **Target-Specific Type Lowering** (`llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/TargetLowering.h`):\n   - `TargetLowering::getValueType()` (line 1740) wraps EVT::getEVT() and handles target-specific pointer types\n   - For PointerType: returns target-specific pointer types via `getPointerTy()`\n   - For VectorType: handles pointer vector elements specially\n\n## SelectionDAG Type Legalization\nThe `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h` defines `DAGTypeLegalizer` which transforms SelectionDAG IR to use only legal target types. The legalization process:\n\n1. **Initialization and Analysis** (`DAGTypeLegalizer::run()` in `LegalizeTypes.cpp` line 200):\n   - Walks all DAG nodes and marks them as `ReadyToProcess` or `Unanalyzed`\n   - Builds a worklist of nodes to legalize\n\n2. **Type Action Resolution** (lines 246-296):\n   - For each result type in a node, calls `getTypeAction()` which queries `TargetLowering::getTypeAction()`\n   - Based on action type (TypePromoteInteger, TypeExpandInteger, TypeSoftenFloat, TypeSplitVector, TypeWidenVector, etc.):\n     - `PromoteIntegerResult()` / `PromoteIntegerOperand()`: Promotes sub-legal integer sizes\n     - `ExpandIntegerResult()` / `ExpandIntegerOperand()`: Splits large integers into smaller ones\n     - `SoftenFloatResult()` / `SoftenFloatOperand()`: Converts floats to integers\n     - `SplitVectorResult()` / `SplitVectorOperand()`: Splits vectors into smaller vectors\n     - `WidenVectorResult()` / `WidenVectorOperand()`: Extends vectors to legal sizes\n\n3. **Type Mapping** (LegalizeTypes.h lines 96-134):\n   - Maintains maps like `PromotedIntegers`, `ExpandedIntegers`, `SoftenedFloats`, `SplitVectors`, `WidenedVectors`\n   - Each maps from the original illegal type to the transformed legal type(s)\n\nThe entire chain flows from abstract LLVM IR types → uniqued types in LLVMContext → machine value types (EVT) → target-legalized types through SelectionDAG's DAGTypeLegalizer."
}

